equation_narrative.headline: Asparagine briefly dominates before late acidic surge delivers glutamate
equation_narrative.story: Position 64 in ubiquitin sits in a charged surface environment near lysine 63, reading structural contacts and co-evolutionary signals through layers 1-23. The representation initially reflects hydrophobic character (leucine peaks at 28% in L4), then shifts toward polar/charged as attention integrates context. Asparagine surges to 59% at L24 as the model transitions to decision-making, but layers 29-33 reverse course dramatically: MLP neurons strongly favoring glutamate activate (N30:672 projects 1.33 toward E, N31:1748 projects 1.51), while asparagine-suppressing neurons fire (N29:4473 erases 1.28 from E toward aromatic residues). Glutamate overtakes asparagine only in the final layer, reaching 64%.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 assemble a complex surface context. Four structural contacts are read, with attention heads at L32 showing strong structural attention (head 18: 0.129 structural, head 13: 0.136 coevol). Early layers show hydrophobic-leaning representation (leucine at 28% L4, valine at 23% L9), consistent with local sequence context. Mid-layers (L13-18) introduce polar character as glycine dominates the logit lens (51% at L13), likely reflecting flexibility or surface-exposure features. By L18, SAE features show mixed signals: F18:244 (14.4 proj, attention) and F18:5271 (13.6 proj) activate without clear chemical specificity. The representation shifts toward polar/charged by L23 as asparagine rises to 22%, suggesting the model has encoded surface-exposed, polar-compatible context.
perception_phase.context_character: Surface-exposed position with mixed polar and charged local environment. Structural contacts and co-evolutionary signals (3 coupled positions) suggest functional constraint, with the representation transitioning from hydrophobic-compatible early to polar/charged-compatible by L23.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 4 residues read via L32 attention heads (head 18: 0.129 structural attn, head 13: 0.136 coevol attn)
Co-evolutionary coupling: 3 positions show evolutionary coordination, integrated through L32 head 13
L9 features: F9:5728 (55.1 proj, attention) and F9:1281 (50.4 proj) encode early context without strong AA specificity
L18 features: F18:244 (14.4 proj) and F18:5271 (13.6 proj) mark transition toward polar character as glycine representation fades

decision_phase.summary: The decision phase begins at L24 with asparagine surging to 59% as prediction channels activate (F24:217 projects 22.6, F24:6298 projects 17.9). Asparagine holds dominance through L29 (22% at L29), but layers 30-33 execute a dramatic reversal. Strong glutamate-specific MLP neurons fire: N30:672 (1.33 proj), N31:1748 (1.51 proj), and N31:816 (1.47 proj) all vote decisively for E. Simultaneously, asparagine-suppressing neurons activate (N29:4473 erases 1.28, N32:1278 erases 0.96). Glutamate overtakes asparagine only at L33, reaching 64% while asparagine collapses to 1.7%.
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary marks the shift from perception to prediction. At L23, the representation is polar-leaning with asparagine at 22%, but no strong AA-specific features. At L24, prediction channels activate: F24:217 (22.6 proj, attention) and F24:6298 (17.9 proj) drive asparagine to 59%, marking the first true prediction commitment. The MLP at L24 shows net negative projection (-2.28), indicating the model is still refining its decision.

candidates.narrative: Glutamate remains below 2% through L29, then surges in the final layers through decisive MLP neuron activation. N30:672 (1.33 proj) and N31:1748 (1.51 proj) are strongly E-specific, voting for glutamate over other charged residues. N31:816 (1.47 proj) adds further support. The final layer sees E jump from 37% to 64%, overtaking asparagine as these late-layer neurons integrate the charged surface context with the specific requirement for a longer acidic side chain (E over D).
key_evidence: N30:672 (1.33 proj) — E-specific neuron with strong preference over K (0.81) and H (0.64)
N31:1748 (1.51 proj) — E-specific neuron, also votes Q (0.82) and H (0.76) but E strongest
N31:816 (1.47 proj) — E-specific with secondary votes for A (0.89) and G (0.82)
F33:179 (88.1 proj, attention) — final-layer feature strongly supporting E

candidates.narrative: Aspartate is the shorter acidic alternative to glutamate, peaking at 27% in the final output. It receives support from similar acidic-favoring neurons but loses the length specificity competition. D appears in top votes for many E-favoring neurons (N30:2296 votes E 1.09, D 0.74; N32:1459 votes D 1.14, E 0.97), suggesting the model recognizes the need for negative charge but ultimately selects the longer glutamate side chain based on structural or evolutionary context.
key_evidence: N30:2296 (1.09 proj to E) — votes D (0.74) as secondary, indicating acidic preference
N32:1459 (0.97 proj to E) — actually votes D stronger (1.14), but net context favors E
Maintains 27% final probability, indicating strong acidic signal but loses length competition

candidates.narrative: Asparagine dominates L24-29, peaking at 59% at L24 as the model transitions to decision-making. This reflects the polar surface context assembled during perception, with N being the polar uncharged alternative to the acidic residues. F24:217 (22.6 proj, attention) and F24:6298 (17.9 proj) drive this surge. However, asparagine collapses in L29-33 as strong suppression neurons fire: N29:4473 (erases 1.28), N32:1278 (erases 0.96). The model ultimately rejects N in favor of the charged glutamate, suggesting evolutionary or structural signals require negative charge rather than just polarity.
candidates.key_layers: Dominates L24-29, peaks at L24 (59%), collapses L30-33
key_evidence: F24:217 (22.6 proj, attention) — drives N surge at decision transition
F24:6298 (17.9 proj, attention) — supports N at L24
N29:4473 (erases 1.28 from E) — votes F (1.39), C (1.11), Y (0.90), suppressing both E and N
N32:1278 (erases 0.96 from E) — votes N (0.83), G (0.75), A (0.75), but net effect suppresses N

candidates.narrative: Leucine peaks at 28% in L4, reflecting the hydrophobic character of the early representation as the model reads local sequence context. The logit lens projects toward L because the accumulated features at this stage correlate with hydrophobic residues, not because the model predicts leucine. This early signal fades by L17 (0.94%) as attention integrates structural contacts and co-evolutionary information revealing the position's surface-exposed, charged character. L never re-emerges in the decision phase, confirming it was a representation artifact rather than a viable candidate.
key_evidence: Early representation is hydrophobic-leaning due to local sequence context (YNIQK[E]STLHL)
Fades as structural and co-evolutionary context accumulates through L8-17
Final probability 2.4%, confirming early signal was representation character, not prediction

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from hydrophobic-leaning to polar/flexible as glycine dominates the logit lens (51% at L13). Attention-driven velocity events at L13 (+3.93 delta, attention-driven), L15 (+3.30, attention), and L16 (+2.78, both) indicate major information integration. F18:244 (14.4 proj) and F18:5271 (13.6 proj) activate, marking the transition toward surface-exposed, polar-compatible context. This is where the model moves from encoding local sequence to encoding structural environment.

The perception-to-decision transition occurs here. At L23, the representation is polar-leaning with no dominant candidate (N at 22%, K at 11%). At L24, asparagine surges to 59% as prediction channels activate (F24:217 projects 22.6, F24:6298 projects 17.9). The MLP at L24 shows strong net negative projection (-2.28), with top erasers N24:4829 (erases 0.50, votes F), N24:3644 (erases 0.43, votes I), indicating the model is actively suppressing hydrophobic alternatives as it commits to polar/charged candidates.

The final reversal occurs as glutamate-specific MLP neurons overwhelm asparagine. L29 shows massive negative velocity (-7.06 at L30, both attn and MLP; -8.95 at L33, MLP-driven), but this represents suppression of asparagine rather than glutamate. N30:672 (1.33 proj), N31:1748 (1.51 proj), and N31:816 (1.47 proj) fire strongly for E. Simultaneously, N29:4473 (erases 1.28) and N32:1278 (erases 0.96) suppress alternatives. Glutamate jumps from 1.6% at L29 to 64% at L33, overtaking asparagine (59% → 1.7%) in the final layer.

deep_dives.label: Structural & coevol attention L32
deep_dives.caption: L32 heads 18 and 13 read structural contacts (0.129 and 0.136 structural attn) and co-evolutionary partners. Head 18 erases 2.90 from E, while head 13 erases 2.57, suggesting these heads gather context that initially favors alternatives before late MLP neurons reinterpret the signal toward glutamate.

deep_dives.label: SAE features L24: decision onset
deep_dives.caption: F24:217 (22.6 proj, attention) and F24:6298 (17.9 proj, attention) are the first strong prediction channels, driving asparagine to 59%. These features mark where the representation shifts from 'polar surface context' to 'asparagine prediction'.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L29-31: E surge
deep_dives.caption: N30:672 (1.33 proj), N31:1748 (1.51 proj), and N31:816 (1.47 proj) are strongly glutamate-specific neurons that fire in the final layers. These neurons distinguish E from other charged residues (K, D) and drive the final decision. Compare their voting patterns to see how the model selects glutamate's longer acidic side chain over aspartate.

deep_dives.label: MLP L29 & L32: N suppression
deep_dives.caption: N29:4473 (erases 1.28 from E, votes F 1.39, C 1.11, Y 0.90) and N32:1278 (erases 0.96, votes N 0.83, G 0.75) actively suppress asparagine in favor of other residues. These neurons are part of the mechanism that collapses N from 59% to 1.7%, even though they don't directly vote for glutamate.

deep_dives.label: SAE features L33: final decision
deep_dives.caption: F33:179 (88.1 proj, attention), F33:7542 (82.6 proj), and F33:7165 (82.2 proj) are the final-layer features that consolidate the glutamate prediction. These high-projection features integrate all prior context into the final 64% confidence output.

deep_dives.label: Velocity L13-18: context shift
deep_dives.caption: Major attention-driven velocity events mark the transition from hydrophobic to polar representation. L13 (+3.93, attention), L15 (+3.30, attention), and L16 (+2.78, both) show when structural and co-evolutionary information overrides local sequence signal. Watch how glycine rises to 51% at L13 as the representation encodes surface-exposed, flexible character.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts glutamate by assembling a charged surface context through layers 1-23, then executing a two-stage decision: first committing to polar/charged candidates (asparagine at 59% by L24), then refining to the specific acidic residue through late-layer MLP neurons (L30-33). The decisive evidence comes from glutamate-specific neurons N30:672, N31:1748, and N31:816, which distinguish E from other charged residues based on side-chain length and chemistry. The asparagine detour at L24-29 reflects the model's initial focus on polarity before evolutionary and structural signals enforce the requirement for negative charge.
